s ideals and laws were adapted, interpreted, and repurposed by those given responsibility to implement them, thereby crafting distinctive, local expressions of Christianity.The vision of Christian community that emerges from Albert's pastoral guide is one in which the messiness of ordinary life is evident. Albert's imagined parish was marked out by geographic and legal boundaries—property and jurisdictional rights, tithes, and sacramental responsibility—as well as symbolic realities. By situating The Mirror of Priests within Albert's physical and conceptual spaces, Klepper affirms the centrality of the parish and its community for those living under the rubric of Christianity, especially outside of large cities. Pivoting between the materiality of texts and the sociocultural contexts of an overlooked manuscript tradition, Pastoral Care and Community in Late Medieval Germany offers fresh insights into the role of parish priests, the pastoral manual genre, and late medieval religious life.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 05. Dez 2022) 0aPastoral carezGermanyxHistoryyTo 1500. 0aPastoral theologyzGermanyxHistoryyTo 1500. 4aGerman Studies. 4aMedieval & Renaissance Studies. 4aReligious Studies. 7aHISTORY / Medieval.2bisacsh  aAlbert of Diessen, late medieval religious life, medieval Christian doctrine and theology, pastoral manual, fourteenth-century pastoral work, religious culture of rural Bavaria, Medieval parish priests, Augustinian canons in medieval Germany.08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertCornell University Press Complete eBook-Package 2022z978311075182640uhttps://doi.org/10.1515/978150176617640uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9781501766176423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9781501766176/original  a978-3-11-075182-6  Cornell University Press Complete eBook-Package 2022b